00:38:50.420 --> 00:38:51.620
it's disturbing your sleep?

00:38:51.620 --> 00:38:53.180
You don't want to
get up at 6:00 ?

00:38:53.180 --> 00:38:54.440
AUDIENCE: Yeah, yeah.

00:38:54.440 --> 00:38:58.350
Like for example, if my
routine is seven to eight hours

00:38:58.350 --> 00:39:01.520
and it starts at
midnight or at 11:00,

00:39:01.520 --> 00:39:03.725
it doesn't work if
the sun rises at 5:00.

00:39:03.725 --> 00:39:04.850
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: Absolutely.

00:39:04.850 --> 00:39:06.470
And if you didn't
have to go to work,

00:39:06.470 --> 00:39:08.420
and you were able to live on
the savannah quite happily,

00:39:08.420 --> 00:39:09.170
you wouldn't mind.

00:39:09.170 --> 00:39:11.032
And you would rise
naturally with dawn.

00:39:11.032 --> 00:39:11.990
And that would be fine.

00:39:11.990 --> 00:39:14.450
Your body clock would
adjust through the year.

00:39:14.450 --> 00:39:16.340
But yes, we all have
other commitments.

00:39:16.340 --> 00:39:20.490
So if you actually want to
sleep for longer, very easy.

00:39:20.490 --> 00:39:23.250
Make sure that you
have blackout blinds.

00:39:23.250 --> 00:39:25.610
Really try and
interfere, actually,

00:39:25.610 --> 00:39:28.680
with that morning sunshine
if that's not what you want.

00:39:28.680 --> 00:39:31.670
Sometimes you will say yes,
but my partner wants the sun.

00:39:31.670 --> 00:39:33.080
What do I do?

00:39:33.080 --> 00:39:34.940
There's a very
simple intervention

00:39:34.940 --> 00:39:36.670
called a sleep mask--

00:39:36.670 --> 00:39:38.540
a soft-- I know.

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:41.540
It's very, very cheap,
very, very simple.

00:39:41.540 --> 00:39:44.180
Often, if you wear one for
a night or two, you're-- oh,

00:39:44.180 --> 00:39:45.290
I don't know about this.

00:39:45.290 --> 00:39:47.748
But actually, most people who
stick to it for three or four

00:39:47.748 --> 00:39:50.420
nights, they're like
oh, actually this really

00:39:50.420 --> 00:39:51.238
makes a difference.

00:39:51.238 --> 00:39:53.280
And one of the advantages
of wearing a sleep mask

00:39:53.280 --> 00:39:55.220
is if you go traveling,
it's something

00:39:55.220 --> 00:39:57.150
you can take with you anywhere.

00:39:57.150 --> 00:39:59.810
And if you are developing a
napping habit because actually,

00:39:59.810 --> 00:40:02.870
you are unable to get enough
sleep during the night,

00:40:02.870 --> 00:40:05.390
having a sleep mask
sort of with you,

00:40:05.390 --> 00:40:07.730
it kind of creates a
little cocoon effect

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:09.690
that can be quite helpful.

00:40:09.690 --> 00:40:13.452
So yeah, if light is disturbing
you, block out the light.

00:40:13.452 --> 00:40:14.660
AUDIENCE: Yeah, thanks a lot.

00:40:14.660 --> 00:40:17.630
So can you speak a bit
about using some medication,

00:40:17.630 --> 00:40:19.430
say melatonin?

00:40:19.430 --> 00:40:21.110
Because I know, for
instance, in the US

00:40:21.110 --> 00:40:23.860
you can buy it in any pharmacy.

00:40:23.860 --> 00:40:27.080
But here you can really--
you need to get prescription.

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:29.365
So is there a kind of
consensus about it?

00:40:29.365 --> 00:40:31.490
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: Yeah, so
that's an interesting one.

00:40:31.490 --> 00:40:34.010
melatonin is a natural
hormone, as we saw.

00:40:34.010 --> 00:40:37.280
It definitely signals to the
body that it's time for sleep.

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:40.770
But what it doesn't do is
override your stress response.

00:40:40.770 --> 00:40:43.280
So it's not a very
powerful hormone

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:45.120
in terms of tackling insomnia.

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:48.220
So the effects of using
melatonin on insomnia

00:40:48.220 --> 00:40:49.490
are pretty much null.

00:40:49.490 --> 00:40:50.990
They're not strong.

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:52.730
What melatonin can
be very helpful

00:40:52.730 --> 00:40:56.180
for is if your body clock is out
of sync with the environment.

00:40:56.180 --> 00:40:58.850
Because it's really something
that influences your body clock

00:40:58.850 --> 00:41:00.810
more than anything.

00:41:00.810 --> 00:41:04.370
So if you're jet-lagged,
actually very, very helpful

00:41:04.370 --> 00:41:07.260
for adjusting over time.

00:41:07.260 --> 00:41:09.740
There are some questions
about melatonin,

00:41:09.740 --> 00:41:11.670
just like most other
natural hormones.

00:41:11.670 --> 00:41:15.140
If you're taking it, does it
mean that your body is actually

00:41:15.140 --> 00:41:17.260
going to produce less?

00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:20.930
And I think that's
a potential concern.

00:41:20.930 --> 00:41:22.880
But I'm not sure
that the research

00:41:22.880 --> 00:41:26.540
is being done long term to work
out whether actually taking

00:41:26.540 --> 00:41:28.670
artificial melatonin
may in some way

00:41:28.670 --> 00:41:30.960
disrupt your natural patterns.

00:41:30.960 --> 00:41:35.000
So with most of these things,
I wouldn't take something

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:37.210
artificial for a long time.

00:41:37.210 --> 00:41:39.500
It'd be much better to
sort your habits out.

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:42.440
But if you have a
short term stress,

00:41:42.440 --> 00:41:46.500
like lots of travel and jet-lag,
I think very, very helpful,

00:41:46.500 --> 00:41:48.260
perhaps.

00:41:48.260 --> 00:41:50.150
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm
just wondering--

00:41:50.150 --> 00:41:51.710
thank you for the talk.

00:41:51.710 --> 00:41:54.350
I'm just wondering what's your
view on the quantification

00:41:54.350 --> 00:41:57.900
and measurement of other sleep
stats all the watches we have,

00:41:57.900 --> 00:41:58.700
et cetera.

00:41:58.700 --> 00:42:01.370
And second question is, any
tips for taking power naps?

00:42:01.370 --> 00:42:04.190
Because sometimes it's very
difficult for me to fall asleep

00:42:04.190 --> 00:42:05.450
after I'm awake.

00:42:05.450 --> 00:42:06.700
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: Yes.

00:42:06.700 --> 00:42:10.140
OK, so first question
about measurement.

00:42:10.140 --> 00:42:14.810
So the only way to
know exactly what's

00:42:14.810 --> 00:42:17.510
going on during the brain--

00:42:17.510 --> 00:42:20.030
in the brain during
sleep, is to measure

00:42:20.030 --> 00:42:23.390
the electrical impulses-- so
an electroencephalogram, which

00:42:23.390 --> 00:42:26.220
will actually tell you the
different stages of sleep.

00:42:26.220 --> 00:42:28.130
And I didn't show it
in the presentation.

00:42:28.130 --> 00:42:29.570
We tend to have
around about sort

00:42:29.570 --> 00:42:32.990
of three main stages of
sleep, and then a REM,

00:42:32.990 --> 00:42:35.030
rapid eye movement, sleep.

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:39.620
So stage one, very light sleep,
can very easily get woken up.

00:42:39.620 --> 00:42:43.070
Few people dipping
into stage one now.

00:42:43.070 --> 00:42:45.170
And then stage two is
a kind of true sleep

00:42:45.170 --> 00:42:47.150
where your body temperature
starts to go down,

00:42:47.150 --> 00:42:48.680
blood pressure
starts to go down.

00:42:48.680 --> 00:42:51.555
But stage three is where it's
very, very hard to wake you up

00:42:51.555 --> 00:42:53.510
and you've got growth
hormone being produced.

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:56.330
And then you come back through
these cycles of REM sleep,

00:42:56.330 --> 00:42:58.880
dream sleep, which is
so important for memory

00:42:58.880 --> 00:43:01.760
consolidation and
emotional balance.

00:43:01.760 --> 00:43:06.710
So basically, we sleep in
these five or six sleep cycles.

00:43:06.710 --> 00:43:10.190
Most of the trackers
that you wear,

00:43:10.190 --> 00:43:12.590
they used to just
rely on movement.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:14.910
And it so happens
that during REM sleep,

00:43:14.910 --> 00:43:17.150
your body is actually paralyzed.

00:43:17.150 --> 00:43:19.265
So-- we think--

00:43:19.265 --> 00:43:21.440
so that you can't
act out your dreams.

00:43:21.440 --> 00:43:24.100
So they use an algorithm
based on your movement

00:43:24.100 --> 00:43:27.200
to kind of predict ah, OK, that
was a period of not moving.

00:43:27.200 --> 00:43:30.290
That must be the end
of the sleep cycle.

00:43:30.290 --> 00:43:32.870
That's not a very good way
of estimating whether or not

00:43:32.870 --> 00:43:34.400
somebody is awake or asleep.

00:43:34.400 --> 00:43:38.270
Because we can all lie very
still and not be sleep.

00:43:38.270 --> 00:43:40.880
The newer new age
kind of trackers,

00:43:40.880 --> 00:43:44.780
which use heart rate
variability or pulse rate, those

00:43:44.780 --> 00:43:45.840
seem to be better.

00:43:45.840 --> 00:43:48.980
But there's been relatively
little published validation

00:43:48.980 --> 00:43:52.272
to show that they are as
good as a polysonogram, where

00:43:52.272 --> 00:43:54.870
you go into the lab and have
lots of things measured.

00:43:54.870 --> 00:43:57.120
But I did see a
small study recently,

00:43:57.120 --> 00:43:59.900
which was using one of the
Fitbit kind of new age--

00:43:59.900 --> 00:44:02.690
which actually showed pretty
good sort of specificity

00:44:02.690 --> 00:44:04.783
and sensitivity to sleep.

00:44:04.783 --> 00:44:06.200
What you probably
don't want to do

00:44:06.200 --> 00:44:08.840
is compare your sleep
to somebody else's sleep

00:44:08.840 --> 00:44:10.340
using those trackers.

00:44:10.340 --> 00:44:14.700
I think it's OK to use
it as a guide for you.

00:44:14.700 --> 00:44:17.570
But then you've got to
ask, why am I using it?

00:44:17.570 --> 00:44:19.820
The best measure
of whether or not

00:44:19.820 --> 00:44:22.690
you are getting
good quality sleep

00:44:22.690 --> 00:44:25.730
is how you feel during the day.

00:44:25.730 --> 00:44:30.150
And your tracker can't
really help you with that.

00:44:30.150 --> 00:44:31.760
The second question
was about naps.

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:33.530
Any top tips for naps?

00:44:33.530 --> 00:44:37.580
So a lot of us will have
this very strong body clock.

00:44:37.580 --> 00:44:41.630
And actually, we won't have a
very strong lull after lunch.

00:44:41.630 --> 00:44:44.030
And it's quite
hard for us to nap.

00:44:44.030 --> 00:44:46.250
If you don't feel
sleepy, don't nap.

00:44:46.250 --> 00:44:49.290
That's one thing.

00:44:49.290 --> 00:44:53.690
It is something to
adapt as a habit.

00:44:53.690 --> 00:44:55.370
Your body clock learns.

00:44:55.370 --> 00:44:58.250
So if you keep
trying and protecting

00:44:58.250 --> 00:45:02.340
your 20 minutes after lunch
when you think you are probably

00:45:02.340 --> 00:45:06.050
in need of a re-boost, even if
you're just sitting quietly,

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:08.520
maybe you're meditating,
it's probably still going

00:45:08.520 --> 00:45:10.268
to have a restorative effect.

00:45:10.268 --> 00:45:11.810
Because you'll
probably still be able

00:45:11.810 --> 00:45:14.570
to up your parasympathetic
nervous system, your rest,

00:45:14.570 --> 00:45:18.290
your digest, and start to
feel physically refreshed even

00:45:18.290 --> 00:45:21.260
if you haven't done all of
the memory kind of recharging

00:45:21.260 --> 00:45:21.960
in the brain.

00:45:21.960 --> 00:45:24.800
So I think it's still
worth having a break

00:45:24.800 --> 00:45:27.600
even if it's not a nap.

00:45:27.600 --> 00:45:30.120
AUDIENCE: OK, I have
a quick question.

00:45:30.120 --> 00:45:32.325
So first of all, thank
you for coming to Google.

00:45:32.325 --> 00:45:33.200
This is really great.

00:45:33.200 --> 00:45:34.158
I've really enjoyed it.

00:45:34.158 --> 00:45:35.510
So thank you for that.

00:45:35.510 --> 00:45:37.352
Quick question
about winding down.

00:45:37.352 --> 00:45:38.810
So for instance,
I have the problem

00:45:38.810 --> 00:45:40.170
of waking up really early.

00:45:40.170 --> 00:45:41.660
So I try to go to bed early.

00:45:41.660 --> 00:45:44.420
But because I'm always on--
like very switched on--

00:45:44.420 --> 00:45:46.863
in the morning I'll wake
up like, 5:00, right?

00:45:46.863 --> 00:45:49.280
And then I can't get back to
sleep until, let's say 6:30--

00:45:49.280 --> 00:45:51.350
a reasonable time to get up.

00:45:51.350 --> 00:45:54.503
So I'm wondering any tactics
for continuing to sleep, right?

00:45:54.503 --> 00:45:56.420
If you've gotten, let's
say, six hours but you

00:45:56.420 --> 00:45:58.520
wake up because
you're kind of wired,

00:45:58.520 --> 00:46:01.370
how do you actually get
yourself, for another hour,

00:46:01.370 --> 00:46:02.055
into sleep mode?

00:46:02.055 --> 00:46:04.430
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: I'm sure
there's a lot of people probably

00:46:04.430 --> 00:46:06.805
in the room who are interested
in the answer to that one.

00:46:06.805 --> 00:46:09.717
And what interested me
there is that you've said,

00:46:09.717 --> 00:46:11.550
you know, I wake up so
early in the morning,

00:46:11.550 --> 00:46:14.310
so I try and go to
bed earlier at night.

00:46:14.310 --> 00:46:16.710
And that's kind of your mistake.

00:46:16.710 --> 00:46:18.620
You're waking up,
exactly as you say,

00:46:18.620 --> 00:46:20.630
because you're a
bit sort of wired.

00:46:20.630 --> 00:46:23.940
You are kind of in this
vigilant sort of state.

00:46:23.940 --> 00:46:27.170
So there's a lot in terms of
the relaxation techniques,

00:46:27.170 --> 00:46:31.310
and learning to detach from all
this exciting stuff going on

00:46:31.310 --> 00:46:32.670
in life.

00:46:32.670 --> 00:46:36.650
But there's also something in
increasing your sleep pressure.

00:46:36.650 --> 00:46:38.810
So one of the things
that we do in CBT

00:46:38.810 --> 00:46:41.870
is to use a technique called
sleep restriction, which

00:46:41.870 --> 00:46:44.090
sounds very counter-intuitive.

00:46:44.090 --> 00:46:47.900
But it actually involves
pushing your bed time back.

00:46:47.900 --> 00:46:50.770
So if you normally
go to bed at 10, say,

00:46:50.770 --> 00:46:53.270
but you're waking up at 5:00
in the morning despite the fact

00:46:53.270 --> 00:46:57.110
that you wanted to sleep
until 7, maybe in that time

00:46:57.110 --> 00:46:59.270
you're only getting
six hours sleep.

00:46:59.270 --> 00:47:02.510
So by tracking your sleep over
a couple of weeks using a sleep

00:47:02.510 --> 00:47:07.610
diary, the advice would be,
OK, try and go to bed at 1:00

00:47:07.610 --> 00:47:09.470
in the morning.

00:47:09.470 --> 00:47:11.400
Set your alarm
for 7:00, whenever

00:47:11.400 --> 00:47:13.550
your desired wake-up time is.

00:47:13.550 --> 00:47:15.920
You're going to get
incredibly tired

00:47:15.920 --> 00:47:18.320
trying to keep yourself awake.

00:47:18.320 --> 00:47:21.290
But you will build up a
stronger sleep pressure.

00:47:21.290 --> 00:47:23.718
And you'll start to
sleep through the night.

00:47:23.718 --> 00:47:25.760
And then as you start to
sleep through the night,

00:47:25.760 --> 00:47:27.650
you can increase
your sleep window.

00:47:27.650 --> 00:47:29.550
The other way to do
it is a slightly sort

00:47:29.550 --> 00:47:30.530
of softer approach.

00:47:30.530 --> 00:47:33.230
Rather than going straight
in for 1:00 in the morning,

00:47:33.230 --> 00:47:35.510
you could just
compress a little bit.

00:47:35.510 --> 00:47:39.230
And keep compressing if it's
not sort of working for you.

00:47:39.230 --> 00:47:41.450
But that sleep
restriction idea gets

00:47:41.450 --> 00:47:44.430
introduced in week three
of the Sleepio program.

00:47:44.430 --> 00:47:49.040
It's probably the single most
powerful technique in CBT

00:47:49.040 --> 00:47:52.640
for helping people reset that
sort of wakefulness early

00:47:52.640 --> 00:47:54.060
in the morning issue.

00:47:54.060 --> 00:47:55.446
So definitely give that a go.

00:47:55.446 --> 00:47:56.773
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:47:56.773 --> 00:47:58.190
AUDIENCE: I'll
sneak in a question

00:47:58.190 --> 00:48:01.740
from someone who is not in the
room-- we have a Dory today.

00:48:01.740 --> 00:48:05.350
So the question is, do alarms
based on the sleep cycle,

00:48:05.350 --> 00:48:07.625
deep versus light, work?

00:48:07.625 --> 00:48:10.250
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: So I think that
relates to the sort of tracking

00:48:10.250 --> 00:48:11.450
question.

00:48:11.450 --> 00:48:15.770
Unless your brain
is cued into a lab,

00:48:15.770 --> 00:48:19.910
it's very difficult to know
what stage of sleep you're in.

00:48:19.910 --> 00:48:22.890
I haven't seen a lot
of convincing evidence,

00:48:22.890 --> 00:48:25.430
but that's probably because
a lot hasn't been published.

00:48:25.430 --> 00:48:28.510
If it works for
you, I say use it.

00:48:28.510 --> 00:48:31.850
And a lot of this kind of sleep
science, it's very individual.

00:48:31.850 --> 00:48:34.710
If there's something
you find reassuring--

00:48:34.710 --> 00:48:36.530
so for example, chamomile tea.

00:48:36.530 --> 00:48:38.180
Some people swear by it.

00:48:38.180 --> 00:48:40.610
The actual evidence
from scientific trials

00:48:40.610 --> 00:48:42.200
is pretty equivocal--

00:48:42.200 --> 00:48:44.700
probably doesn't
really do very much.

00:48:44.700 --> 00:48:47.420
But there's a very
strong placebo effect.

00:48:47.420 --> 00:48:50.750
Anything that makes you feel
like you are sleeping well

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:53.400
is probably a good idea
for you, personally.

00:48:53.400 --> 00:48:57.225
Even if the science is
a bit kind of shaky.

00:48:57.225 --> 00:48:59.510
AUDIENCE: Hi, what
do you recommend

00:48:59.510 --> 00:49:02.020
for winding down at night?

00:49:02.020 --> 00:49:04.730
The other question is if I
want to go to bed at 11:00,

00:49:04.730 --> 00:49:07.640
is it a bad idea to go to the
gym like between 9:00 and 10:00

00:49:07.640 --> 00:49:08.450
in the evening?

00:49:08.450 --> 00:49:12.710
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: OK, I'll take
off at the gym one first.

00:49:12.710 --> 00:49:14.780
It used to be thought--
the advice used to be

00:49:14.780 --> 00:49:17.050
not to exercise late at night.

00:49:17.050 --> 00:49:19.490
And the reason being because
it increases your body

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:20.180
temperature.

00:49:20.180 --> 00:49:22.070
It really gets the body going.

00:49:22.070 --> 00:49:24.350
And there was some
evidence that absolutely,

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:26.940
if your body is too
hot, you cannot sleep.

00:49:26.940 --> 00:49:30.590
So one of the things I didn't
mention is to cool your room.

00:49:30.590 --> 00:49:34.970
So an ideal room temperature
is 18 degrees, supposedly,

00:49:34.970 --> 00:49:37.640
with air circulating
if possible.

00:49:37.640 --> 00:49:40.333
So subsequent to
that, the advice

00:49:40.333 --> 00:49:41.750
is actually some
people are really

00:49:41.750 --> 00:49:45.440
quite effective at cooling down,
like mentally and physically,

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:46.790
after they've been to the gym.

00:49:46.790 --> 00:49:50.060
So I would have thought that if
you're doing something highly

00:49:50.060 --> 00:49:53.270
aerobic, it's going to take
you at least an hour if not 90

00:49:53.270 --> 00:49:56.180
minutes to properly
calm down after that.

00:49:56.180 --> 00:49:59.210
So you want to allow
enough time for that.

00:49:59.210 --> 00:50:02.210
But this is about being
a scientist of yourself

00:50:02.210 --> 00:50:03.950
and kind of experimenting.

00:50:03.950 --> 00:50:06.290
You know, if you push that
exercise time a little bit

00:50:06.290 --> 00:50:08.430
forward, does it make you
sleep better, and so on?

00:50:08.430 --> 00:50:10.880
Because it will be different
for different people.

00:50:10.880 --> 00:50:14.750
In terms of the
wind down routine,

00:50:14.750 --> 00:50:17.270
you can ask parents what
they do for their kids,

00:50:17.270 --> 00:50:20.540
and everyone's probably got
a slightly different pattern.

00:50:20.540 --> 00:50:21.843
But they get into a pattern.

00:50:21.843 --> 00:50:23.010
And that's what's important.

00:50:23.010 --> 00:50:24.520
That's what gets reassuring.

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:26.660
It doesn't matter if you
have a bath or a shower,

00:50:26.660 --> 00:50:28.490
or you read, or you meditate.

00:50:28.490 --> 00:50:30.710
I know that Google's got
some really good resources.

00:50:30.710 --> 00:50:31.502
I know you've got--

00:50:31.502 --> 00:50:33.120
Headspace is
available if you want

00:50:33.120 --> 00:50:36.200
to learn mindfulness meditation.

00:50:36.200 --> 00:50:40.510
Just reading a book
that is not energizing,

00:50:40.510 --> 00:50:43.790
sort of alerting,
light-filled experience,

00:50:43.790 --> 00:50:46.670
watching TV so long as you are
far enough away that you're not

00:50:46.670 --> 00:50:49.130
getting overstimulated
by the content.

00:50:49.130 --> 00:50:51.350
I definitely wouldn't do
that right before bed,

00:50:51.350 --> 00:50:53.990
but as part of an hour-long
wind down routine, that

00:50:53.990 --> 00:50:54.990
might be fine.

00:50:54.990 --> 00:50:57.920
It's just about psychological
and physical kind

00:50:57.920 --> 00:51:01.650
of detachment from the day.

00:51:01.650 --> 00:51:04.360
AUDIENCE: Yes, I wanted to
ask you about noise in the

00:51:04.360 --> 00:51:06.530
because we talked about
light in the morning.

00:51:06.530 --> 00:51:08.850
Like earplugs-- I
mean, maybe it's not

00:51:08.850 --> 00:51:10.620
good to use them every night.

00:51:10.620 --> 00:51:13.530
I'm wondering about other ways--
can you train yourself to not

00:51:13.530 --> 00:51:15.660
be sensitive to noise,
or noise generators,

00:51:15.660 --> 00:51:16.710
or what do you suggest?

00:51:16.710 --> 00:51:18.670
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: Good question.

00:51:18.670 --> 00:51:21.630
Some people definitely
find white noise machines

00:51:21.630 --> 00:51:22.950
very useful.

00:51:22.950 --> 00:51:26.050
This doesn't have to be
something very expensive.

00:51:26.050 --> 00:51:27.930
It could be a fan.

00:51:27.930 --> 00:51:29.328
I think Wayne
Rooney swore by it.

00:51:29.328 --> 00:51:31.120
He said he couldn't
sleep without the noise

00:51:31.120 --> 00:51:33.037
of the washing machine
or something like that.

00:51:33.037 --> 00:51:35.670
There are certain noises
which block out other sounds.

00:51:35.670 --> 00:51:39.030
So a fan and similiar
can be quite good.

00:51:39.030 --> 00:51:42.180
An artificial noise
machine, absolutely fine.

00:51:42.180 --> 00:51:45.300
There isn't any evidence that
so long as it's not too loud,

00:51:45.300 --> 00:51:47.610
that that's going to
disrupt your sleep.

00:51:47.610 --> 00:51:49.560
I also don't think
there are any issues

00:51:49.560 --> 00:51:53.400
with using earplugs
long term, provided

00:51:53.400 --> 00:51:55.830
that they're good quality.

00:51:55.830 --> 00:51:59.470
But I wouldn't worry about
using earplugs as a negative.

00:51:59.470 --> 00:52:02.670
I think, actually
it's quite sensible.

00:52:02.670 --> 00:52:05.350
SPEAKER: Time for
one more question.

00:52:05.350 --> 00:52:07.560
AUDIENCE: Oh wow, thank you.

00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:08.610
We could go on.

00:52:08.610 --> 00:52:11.760
So during the week, I
rarely get enough sleep.

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:14.280
And then on the weekend,
I do sleep longer.

00:52:14.280 --> 00:52:15.660
Is that sufficient?

00:52:15.660 --> 00:52:18.840
I mean, you talked about
the brain self-repairing.

00:52:18.840 --> 00:52:21.330
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: Yeah,
so here's the thing.

00:52:21.330 --> 00:52:23.100
It's better to sleep
than not to sleep.

00:52:23.100 --> 00:52:25.200
So great that you're making
an effort to catch up

00:52:25.200 --> 00:52:26.290
on sleep at the weekend.

00:52:26.290 --> 00:52:28.530
But for every night
of short sleep,

00:52:28.530 --> 00:52:29.973
you are feeling those effects.

00:52:29.973 --> 00:52:32.640
On your Tuesday, your Wednesday,
your Thursday, and your Friday,

00:52:32.640 --> 00:52:34.140
you are building
up that sleep debt.

00:52:34.140 --> 00:52:36.210
So by Friday afternoon,
I hope you're not

00:52:36.210 --> 00:52:37.800
operating heavy machinery.

00:52:37.800 --> 00:52:40.590
But it's not ideal.

00:52:40.590 --> 00:52:43.620
If you can find even just
an extra half an hour

00:52:43.620 --> 00:52:45.390
during the week, what
you'll actually find

00:52:45.390 --> 00:52:47.358
is that you have more weekend.

00:52:47.358 --> 00:52:48.900
You've got more of
a life because you

00:52:48.900 --> 00:52:51.480
don't have to worry about
catching up on your sleep.

00:52:51.480 --> 00:52:53.520
The other thing is that
come Monday morning,

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:55.800
you're effectively
giving yourself jet-lag

00:52:55.800 --> 00:52:59.550
if you have a different pattern
during the week to the weekend.

00:52:59.550 --> 00:53:02.670
And there is some research
evidence that come out

00:53:02.670 --> 00:53:04.650
suggesting that of
this sort of pattern--

00:53:04.650 --> 00:53:06.990
we do call it social jet-lag--

00:53:06.990 --> 00:53:10.770
could increase risks of high
blood pressure, of weight gain.

00:53:10.770 --> 00:53:15.280
It's putting more pressure on
your body than is necessary.

00:53:15.280 --> 00:53:18.890
So if you can find more
of a balance, great.

00:53:20.823 --> 00:53:22.490
SPEAKER: All right,
thank you very much.

00:53:22.490 --> 00:53:23.573
SOPHIE BOSTOCK: Thank you.

00:53:23.573 --> 00:53:27.940
[APPLAUSE]

